Observers: Kim Eckert and Minnesota Birding Weeks group including Alberta Adams, Cindy and Chris Edwardson, Peggy Jenkins (Sacramento, CA), Becky and Mark Lystig, Dennis Randall, Lee Randall, Sharon Robertson, Shelley Steva, Peder Svingen, and Sandra Tholen (Wichita, KS). Estimated traveling distance during excursion with O'Brien's Boat Tours in Bay Bulls (709) 753-4850 to Witless Bay Ecological Preserve. The reserve, encompassing Gull Island, Green Island, Great Island, and Pee Pee Island, contains North America's largest Atlantic puffin colony. More than 260,000 pairs of the province's official bird nest here during the late spring and summer (133,600 breeding pairs according to Witless Bay IBA web site). Witless Bay Ecological Reserve also hosts the second-largest (after Baccalieu Island Ecological Reserve) Leach's storm-petrel colony in the world; more than 620,000 pairs come here to nest. Other nesting seabirds include Common Murrre (Turre) -- 78,400 breeding pairs on Great, Green, and Gull Is.; Thick-billed Murre -- 600 breeding pairs on Green Island; Razorbill (Tinker) -- 330 brreeding pairs on Gull and Green Is.; and Black-legged Kittiwake (Tickle-ace) -- 38,430 breeding pairs on Great, Green, and Gull Is. We also observed and photographed humpback whales and Atlantic white-sided dolphins.		obs61176	Peder	Svingen	S8572519	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	160	20		13	1		1	0

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS123058923	4620	species	Atlantic Puffin	Fratercula arctica			8			Canada	CA	Newfoundland and Labrador	CA-NL	Avalon Peninsula-St. John's	CA-NL-ON	CA-NF_015	St. Shotts--Stage Shore	L1235428	P	46.6220612	-53.5964155	2011-07-10	10:35:00	Observers: Kim Eckert and Minnesota Birding Weeks group including Alberta Adams, Cindy and Chris Edwardson, Peggy Jenkins (Sacramento, CA), Becky and Mark Lystig, Dennis Randall, Lee Randall, Sharon Robertson, Shelley Steva, Peder Svingen, and Sandra Tholen (Wichita, KS). During a one hour sea watch off the Stage Shore cliffs southwest of the town of St. Shotts, we witnessed an incredible flight of shearwaters, gannets, kittiwakes, and even a few storm-petrels relatively close to shore. The birds were streaming by in a southeasterly direction during very strong southwesterly winds (measured at up to 110 km/hr at nearby stations). As far as we could tell, the birds were not successfully finding food and as far as we could tell they were not aimlessly circling the area since they disappeared to the southeast after passing by our position. We parked our vehicles close to the edge of the cliff and stayed in our vehicles since it was impossible to set up a spotting scope or to safely stand outside. Birds were counted only if they were close enough to shore to identify through binoculars. Total numbers were estimated based on the number of birds of each species seen in a minute of observation; e.g., we estimated 250 Sooty Shearwaters per minute for a total of 15,000 individuals for the hour long observation. There was never a lull throughout the entire hour and unidentified shearwaters could be seen in the far distance. I took a series of photographs with a 400 mm lens during this time which show an average of 6 to 8 shearwaters in each frame; this suggests that the total number of shearwaters was probably much higher since 6 to 8 birds per second would be 21,600 to 21,800 per hour and the field of view of a 400 mm lens captured only a small fraction of the birds visible at any point in time. Subsequent postings by Dave Shephard and Dave Brown also documented exceptional numbers of Sooty Shearwaters off the south coast of the Avalon Peninsula in mid-July. For example, on 18 July 2011 Dave Brown wrote, "There were legendary numbers of Sooty Shearwaters at Daley's Cove today. There was a continuous string in flight and sitting on the water all the way from Daleys' Cove to the Drook. I never even tried to estimate numbers  but 50,000 would probably be very conservative. Approximate totals are as follows: Sooty Shearwater- 50,000+ Greater Shearwater- 500-1000 Manx Shearwater- 16 Northern Fulmar- 6 (all light phase) Pomarine Jaeger- 6 ( all subadults 1-3 years) LONG-TAILED JAEGER- 1 near adult bird sitting on water at Daley's Cove, 100m from shore for almost 20 minutes Jaeger sp- 2. There were also multitudes of Kittiwakes and lots of Common Murres, Puffins and a lesser number of Razorbills..."		obs61176	Peder	Svingen	S8578626	eBird - Stationary Count	EBIRD	60			13	1	G280004	1	0

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS123073321	4620	species	Atlantic Puffin	Fratercula arctica			8			Canada	CA	Newfoundland and Labrador	CA-NL	Avalon Peninsula-St. John's	CA-NL-ON	CA-NF_015	St. Shotts--Stage Shore	L1235428	P	46.6220612	-53.5964155	2011-07-10	10:35:00	Observers: Kim Eckert and Minnesota Birding Weeks group including Alberta Adams, Cindy and Chris Edwardson, Peggy Jenkins (Sacramento, CA), Becky and Mark Lystig, Dennis Randall, Lee Randall, Sharon Robertson, Shelley Steva, Peder Svingen, and Sandra Tholen (Wichita, KS). During a one hour sea watch off the Stage Shore cliffs southwest of the town of St. Shotts, we witnessed an incredible flight of shearwaters, gannets, kittiwakes, and even a few storm-petrels relatively close to shore. The birds were streaming by in a southeasterly direction during very strong southwesterly winds (measured at up to 110 km/hr at nearby stations). As far as we could tell, the birds were not successfully finding food and as far as we could tell they were not aimlessly circling the area since they disappeared to the southeast after passing by our position. We parked our vehicles close to the edge of the cliff and stayed in our vehicles since it was impossible to set up a spotting scope or to safely stand outside. Birds were counted only if they were close enough to shore to identify through binoculars. Total numbers were estimated based on the number of birds of each species seen in a minute of observation; e.g., we estimated 250 Sooty Shearwaters per minute for a total of 15,000 individuals for the hour long observation. There was never a lull throughout the entire hour and unidentified shearwaters could be seen in the far distance. I took a series of photographs with a 400 mm lens during this time which show an average of 6 to 8 shearwaters in each frame; this suggests that the total number of shearwaters was probably much higher since 6 to 8 birds per second would be 21,600 to 21,800 per hour and the field of view of a 400 mm lens captured only a small fraction of the birds visible at any point in time. Subsequent postings by Dave Shephard and Dave Brown also documented exceptional numbers of Sooty Shearwaters off the south coast of the Avalon Peninsula in mid-July. For example, on 18 July 2011 Dave Brown wrote, "There were legendary numbers of Sooty Shearwaters at Daley's Cove today. There was a continuous string in flight and sitting on the water all the way from Daleys' Cove to the Drook. I never even tried to estimate numbers  but 50,000 would probably be very conservative. Approximate totals are as follows: Sooty Shearwater- 50,000+ Greater Shearwater- 500-1000 Manx Shearwater- 16 Northern Fulmar- 6 (all light phase) Pomarine Jaeger- 6 ( all subadults 1-3 years) LONG-TAILED JAEGER- 1 near adult bird sitting on water at Daley's Cove, 100m from shore for almost 20 minutes Jaeger sp- 2. There were also multitudes of Kittiwakes and lots of Common Murres, Puffins and a lesser number of Razorbills..."		obs275698	Chris	Edwardson	S8579804	eBird - Stationary Count	EBIRD	60			13	1	G280004	1	0

I found Long-tailed Duck, Pink-footed Goose, and Gyrfalcon, but amazingly missed Snow Bunting. Drove back south, crossing east on Rt. 59 and checking shorebird at Boreyri before dark. Pulled n at north side of river at Bldus for the night at about 00:30. WEATHER: Cool, comparatively calm, with intermittent light drizzle. Almost no wind, especially inafternoon when seas were flat calm. L476343	P	42.6051578	-70.5672455	2009-02-01	08:00:00	All observations from 7 Seas whale-watch boat Privateer IV under Jay Frontierro, part of the first (annual) Cape Ann Winter Birding Weekend, sponsored by the Cape Ann Chamber of Commerce and Mass Audubon. The boat left Gloucester harbor at 8 and returned at 1145. We went up the ocean side of Cape Ann past the Dry Salvages toward the southern end of Jeffreys Ledge and returned the same way, though in some places closer to shore. We were unable to find the king eider off Salt Island, and though some people may have seen purple sandpipers, I did not see any. We traveled south from Rye into MA waters to an area east of Gloucester known as Tillie''s Bank.  This has been an active area for whales recently and this is where almost all of the whales were seen today.  We then traveled northward to NH waters along Jeffrey''s Ledge, before finishing by traveling back home through the Isles of Shoals.  Great trip highlighted by a spectacular whale show as well as spectacular views of a juvenile Sabine''s Gull and a juvenile Atlantic Puffin.  Thanks to Jon Woolf for organizing this successful trip, Lauren Kras for diligently chumming for the skua that never showed, and to Captain Pete Reynolds and crew for skillfully working the birds and whales we encountered.----Map of trip:---------------------http://home.comcast.net/~smirick//NH%20Audubon%20Pelagic%20-%20091310.jpg----Great photos of birds and mammals by Len Medlock-----------------------------------------------------------------------------http://www.pbase.com/lmedlock/9132010------8:00 AM - 5:00 PM--Overcast skies with excellent visibility.--Seas 1 to 3 feet--Winds - S to SSE winds.  5 to 15 knots.--Birders - 26----Total List for all waters (eBird reports from various locations have been submitted)---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------Common Eider--Common Loon - 2 migrating offshore.--NORTHERN FULMAR - 1. Mysterious first storm-petrel of the day.  Quickly disappeared, but some saw dark rump on bird.--Northern Gannet - 90--Double-crested Cormorant--Great Cormorant - 12  all on Isles of Shoals. Three groups of birds.  Nice views.  All in MA waters.--SABINE''S GULL - 1.  Spectacular views of juvenile swimming with Laughing Gull right next to boat!  In MA waters.--Bonaparte''s Gull - 2--Laughing Gull - 14--Ring-billed Gull--Herring Gull--LESSER BLACK-BACKED GULL - 3.  All adults in NH waters.  Great views of one bird out on ledge. We traveled south from Rye into MA waters to an area east of Gloucester known as Tillie''s Bank.  This has been an active area for whales recently and this is where almost all of the whales were seen today.  We then traveled northward to NH waters along Jeffrey''s Ledge, before finishing by traveling back home through the Isles of Shoals.  Great trip highlighted by a spectacular whale show as well as spectacular views of a juvenile Sabine''s Gull and a juvenile Atlantic Puffin. Thanks to Jon Woolf for organizing this successful trip, Lauren Kras for diligently chumming for the skua that never showed, and to Captain Pete Reynolds and crew for skillfully working the birds and whales we encountered.----Map of trip:---------------------http://home.comcast.net/~smirick//NH%20Audubon%20Pelagic%20-%20091310.jpg----Great photos of birds and mammals by Len Medlock-----------------------------------------------------------------------------http://www.pbase.com/lmedlock/9132010------8:00 AM - 5:00 PM--Overcast skies with excellent visibility.--Seas 1 to 3 feet--Winds - S to SSE winds.  5 to 15 knots.--Birders - 26----Total List for all waters (eBird reports from various locations have been submitted)---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------Common Eider--Common Loon - 2 migrating offshore.--NORTHERN FULMAR - 1. The cumulative offshore trip totals were: White-winged Scoter - 2, Northern Fulmar - 3, Red-throated Loon - 2, Common Loon - 23, Northern Gannet - 100, Black-legged Kittiwake - 6, Bonaparte's Gull - 8, Herring Gull - 26, Lesser Black-backed Gull - 1, Great Black-backed Gull - 20, Dovekie - 2,334, Common Murre - 1, Razorbill - 69, large alcid (sp.) - 1, Atlantic Puffin - 3	<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/35144142@N04/6846164459/" title="Atlantic Puffin 2012 Feb 4 MD Pelagic by pgbird85, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7207/6846164459_59a5e5f351.jpg" alt="Atlantic Puffin 2012 Feb 4 MD Pelagic"></a>	obs148762	Jeff	Shenot	S10124353	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	30	4.86		22	1	G368441	1	1

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS101523031	4620	species	Atlantic Puffin	Fratercula arctica			1			United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Hancock	US-ME-009		Jordan Basin Gulf of Maine November 16, 2010 	L1026302	P	44.0007178	-67.8639221	2010-11-16	04:30:00	Tuesday November 16,  2010----Right Whale Jordan Basin Transects,   Boston Aquarium,    Mo  Brown , the  Bar Harbor Whale Watch Company and crew of the Friendship 5.  It was a pleasure to be back the Friendship 5 where I worked as a naturalist in 1994 and a total pleasure to be asked to count sea birds. ----Leaving  in the dark at  4:30 am  we departed  for the 2 hour cruise to Jordan Basin to investigate  a newly discovered  and potential breeding ground for Right Whales off the Maine coast.   None of the crew had previously been to this area in Jordan Basin  so we were all excited and anticipation of a great day helped us deal with the slight discomfort of seasickness!  The start of the transects and last known location of many  Right Whales congregating  was about 55 miles off shore.  Transects were run  Northeast  to Southwest.   These transects at times  did overlap,  partly due to dense fog and overcast conditions early in the morning,   so we were somewhat careful to not over estimate the numbers of birds we were seeing and counting.  That said,  these data indicate  that this location is definitely a place of interest and  an important  feeding and winter location for Dovekie.  Future trips to the region will help verify this and would like to ask for help in filling in the gaps of Dovekie life histories.   We are very interested in any information you might have on Dovekie in the Gulf of Maine. ---- The first bird of the day at 6:15 AM was a Greater Shearwater followed by calming seas,  dense fog , than  clearing to 5+ miles. We all greatly enjoyed being around so many Right Whales  and I think  we had 11-13 individuals including an amazing female that breached 4 times,  200-300  White-sided Dolphins also help put smiles on our faces seeing them darting, jumping and  moving about with  and around the Right Whales.    ----We had many  excellent birds sightings throughout the day foraging among the Right whales .    Definitely the bird of the day   were the 214 DOVEKIE  that we found along our transects  which indicated to all of us that there were thousands out there.  Many Dovekie flocks were seen of upwards of  10-30  birds and both Zack Klyver  and I commented that this was the most Dovekie we have ever seen on one day!  We had one Atlantic Puffin , 2 Razorbills and 6 Common Murre.    We also had 105 Northern Fulmar including 6 Gray Phase.   I realized this morning that one important group of birds we saw were  3 Red-breasted Merganser indicating again, that this area of the GOM is a known feeding ground for many species of birds!  Its all about food in the winter.  ----What we want to find out is if anyone out there knows of other work done that has documented so many Dovekie in the GOM and specific sites.  If you have information we would be very interested in continuing the discussion.  Jordan Basin clearly  is an important  location for further future research to see if this is a preferred fall/winter  migratory  stopover  for Dovekie  and a broad assortment of other Seabirds.   From the amount of wildlife in this region of the Gulf  and specifically the endangered Right Whale,   this should be a protected  and highly regulated zone of the Jordan Basin. This work can only occur through multidisciplinary oceanographic investigations .----Michael ------Greater Shearwater   57--Northern  Fulmar   105--Northern Gannet   15    (14 adult, 1 3rd year bird) --Dbl-crested Cormorant   3--Herring Gull   43--Laughing Gull   1 --Great Black-backed Gull     imm.  22--       Adult  26--Black-legged Kittiwake  38    Mostly adults in winter plumage and a few 1st winter --Phalarope  sp.    2--Red-breasted Merganser         3--Puffin sp.     2--Atlantic Puffin   1--Razorbill   2--DOVEKIE            214+  breeding and non-breeding plumage scampering and diving for food--Common Murre   6   deep in the fog flyby--Unidentified    1000+   many birds were simply too far away------November 16, 2010 --6:15 first bird--7:11  fog  and l		obs224998	Michael J. A detailed report will follow.  Landing on the ship or flying with us were 1 Song Sparrow, 1 Dark-eyed Junco adult, 1 Brown-headed Cowbird, 1 Pine Siskin and a female American Goldfinch.  Todays transects represent new territory covered by our team and some differences should be noted from my last report.  The farther away from the basin edge we got,  the number of Dovekie diminished as we got farther out into the GOM. When scanning the waters this time with my spotting scope,  there would be large areas without birds in general and Dovekie in particular. There still seemed to be a tight correlation between when we saw Dovekie/birds and Whales together although there were Dovekie scattered throughout the transects where we were not seeing whales . This weeks transects still showed many Dovekie associated with the transect area albeit with numbers slightly smaller than last trip which cover ares East and north. Weather was Blue skis, seas 1 foot, 24 - 40 degrees F and unlimited visibility. A great day over all 		obs224998	Michael J. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS103741564	4620	species	Atlantic Puffin	Fratercula arctica			6			United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Hancock	US-ME-009		Jorda Basin Dec 18, 2010 	L1046679	P	43.5963059	-67.8955078	2010-12-18	06:00:00	 Jordan Basin /Outer Falls 12/18/2010 ----Location: Jordan Basin /Outer Falls ----Observation date: 12/18/10 (6:00AM  4:00PM)--Weather: Patchy Blue skis am, seas choppy  3-4 foot,  14-28 degrees F, steady 10-15 mph wind, visibility 4-5 miles, partly sunny to 70% patchwork clouds in the PM.  --Red sky at night sailors delight with a breaching Right Whale at 4:25pm.  ----Principal Investigator: Dr. Moira Brown, (New England Aquarium/Canadian Whale Institute). Contact at mwbrown@neaq.org .----Seabird Observers: Michael Good, recorder (Down East Nature Tours), Laura Kennedy (UMO, Orono), Zack Klyver, (Bar Harbor Whale Watch Company). ----Notes: We would like to report on the New England Aquarium Right Whale research team and Canadian Whale Institutes second late fall/winter 2010 survey cruise for principally right whales and also other marine mammals and seabirds. Our survey area is located approximately 50 to 70 miles SW of Schoodic Peninsula, Frenchmans Bay, and Bar Harbor, Maine; in an area just west of Jordan Basin and east of a high bottom area known as Outer Falls. ----We conducted two survey transect lines that were five miles apart at a speed of about 13 knots. Throughout the surveys we regular fell off the transect lines or came to a complete stop to conduct photo ID of individual right whales.  Our first transect line was approx. thirty miles long and ran in a NE to SW direction beginning at approx. 4331.19 X 06802.59 and ending at approx. 4315.79 X 06835.56. Our second transect line was approx. twenty miles long and ran in a SW to NE direction, beginning at approx. 4316.79 X 06833.62 and ending at approx. 4326.12 X 06813.89. ----A bow watch was maintained throughout the entire cruise for seabirds and all sightings were recorded in 30-minute intervals. Distance sampling along a transect line is typically used for monitoring changes of bird abundance at sea. Following the distance sampling assumptions and results of Lucas et al. (Condor 112(3): 455-459) we could reliable identify birds from 1 to 300 meters from the ship with 4-5 miles visibility for the larger birds. Some distortions caused by different densities of air resulting in a change in the refractive index made identification challenging as did the cold temperatures. If Thick-billed Murre (Uria lomvia) were present they would have been easily detected in the high probability zone 0-50 meters from the ship.  I had no definitive identification of Thick Billed Murre.  ----Please note that some of the more highly mobile seabird species (i.e. Northern Fulmar and B. L. Kittiwake  See Fig. 2-4) may have crossed over transects and could have been counted twice. No Passerines were sighted on this trip.  ----We did have 3 different flocks of Canada Geese that were clearly trans-Gulf of Maine migrants on strong northeasterly winds.  Of the Alcids we observed Common Murre (87) had the greatest abundance followed by Dovekie (48).----Of particular interest were our Dovekie and Common Murre  sightings, which correlated with whale sightings. The total  number of bird species was high between 7 to 8 am when whales were present.  From 8-12:00 a relative dearth of birds sub-zero temperatures and steady wind. Numbers of whales low coinciding with low bird numbers.  Around 12:00 Whales and birds increase.  B-l Kittiwake (20), N. Fulmar (16), C.Murre(1) and Dovekie (9)  Canada Geese (24), Wht-w Scoter (4)  and whales. Abundance and density of birds remains low until 4:30 pm.  ----Figure 1. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS43632270	4620	species	Atlantic Puffin	Fratercula arctica			25			United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Washington	US-ME-029		Maine Pelagic	L456010	P	44.3552782	-67.0605469	2007-09-29		Maine Audubon Society pelagic led by Lysle Brinker, Jan Pierson, et al. aboard the Friendship V, a fast cat. Afforded great views of nearly all species. The DEJU landed on the boat, while the PUFI appeared it was going to, but never did. The Great Skua flew in and started pounding the crap out of a bird on the water for about 10 seconds, and then it flew off. We were unable to chase due to the number of whales around us, which included Finback, Humpback, and Minke Whales. One humpback gave us a show with its tail slapping. Other mammals included Harbor and Gray seals, Harbor Porpoises, and White-sided Dolphins. Also seen were several Bluefin Tuna leaping out of the water. The trip went as far east as Grand Manan Island, and a little bit beyond.		obs96561	James	Restivo	S3134954	eBird - Casual Observation	EBIRD				30	0		1	0

Great birds but marine mammals stole the show with eight species of cetacean including Harbor Porpoise, Atlantic White-sided Dolphin, numerous Humpback Whales, 50+ Pilot Whales, 1 Fin Whale, 2 Minke Whale, 1 Right Whale, and a SPERM WHALE!!!! URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS77451232	4620	species	Atlantic Puffin	Fratercula arctica			5			United States	US	New Hampshire	US-NH	Rockingham	US-NH-015		Star Island to Jeffreys Ledge, NH	L799666	P	42.8970946	-70.6043243	1972-11-12	08:00:00	This was my first New England pelagic trip, sponsored by NH Audubon out of Portsmouth, and one of the best I ever had. It included a one-hour stop at Star Island in the Isles of Shoals, where the landbirds were. The birders were from many states and included Gene Eisenmann from AMNH, Guy McKaskie, Davis Finch, Dick Veit, and many other great birders that I can''t even remember. I can remember the thrill of seeing those dovekies, puffins, and fulmars (both morphs) to this day. None of the flagged numbers were out of line, and there were plenty of crack birders counting them. Others saw quite a few more species that I missed, and I am not including them here. The one I most regret not seeing was red phalarope; I don''t know how many were seen.		obs52135	Jim	Berry	S5513653	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	480	64.372		40	1		1	1

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS50428751	4620	species	Atlantic Puffin	Fratercula arctica			1			United States	US	New Hampshire	US-NH	Rockingham	US-NH-015		Plaice Cove	L730953	P	42.9435751	-70.7877874	2007-06-10			Adult in breeding plumage offshore from rocky point just north of Bicentennial Park in Hampton.  We hiked out to watch a flock of terns here, and I noted a distant alcid on the water and immediately thought Atlantic Puffin, but the distance and heat shimmer were difficult.  We walked a distance out onto the slippery rocks (low tide) and got closer views with much less shimmer to clearly see an adult puffin!  We watched it for about 15 minutes as it flapped its wings and eventually took off and headed southward toward Great Boar's Head.  Decent looks at big orange bill and large white face bordered by black and dark eye and solid black back.  In flight noted stocky look with dark underwings and alcid type flight.  My first shore-based (and only 2nd NH) record, but not entirely unexpected given their increase along the Maine coast and their increasingly regular summer appearance out on White & Seavey Islands. 	obs130978	Stephen	Mirick	S3632445	eBird - Casual Observation	EBIRD					0		1	1

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS135910961	4620	species	Atlantic Puffin	Fratercula arctica			1			United States	US	New Hampshire	US-NH	Rockingham	US-NH-015		Jeffreys Ledge--NH	L569900	H	42.9222405	-70.52948	2012-01-11		All day trip with Eric Masterson aboard the UNH research vessel "Gulf Challenger".  The boat traveled east from New Castle, NH toward Jeffrey's Ledge and beyond to Wilkinson's Basin.  The boat collected and tested sea water samples before returning.  The course of the boat took it through ME, NH, and MA waters and stopped at a few locations for periods of 20 minutes or longer to collect water samples.  It did not change course for birds.  Here is the track of the boat with state boundaries in red.----http://home.comcast.net/~smirick//PelagicTrip011112.jpg----Birds were thinly scattered, but relatively consistent beyond the Isles of Shoals with almost zero large gulls on Jeffrey's Ledge.  The exception was around two distant (1+ miles) trawlers where there were large numbers of uncounted gulls (and likely fulmar, kittiwakes, etc) attending the vessels. Overflow from one of these boats resulted in a good count of birds in deep water near Wilkinson's Basin in MA waters.----8:15 AM - 4:00 PM--Weather - Mostly sunny in morning, becoming mostly cloudy on return trip.  Unlimited visibility.--Winds - 10 knots out of the North, shifting to East on return trip.--Seas - 3 feet----Total list of birds submitted in 4 separate eBird lists----------------------------------------------------------------------American Black Duck     2  moving south together east of Isles of shoals (migrating?)--Common Eider     11 moving south in two groups.  8 just east of Isles of shoals, 3 more well offshore east of Jeffrey's Ledge (migrating?)--Long-tailed Duck     1 male moving south by itself on Jeffrey's Ledge (migrating?)--Northern Fulmar     52  (38 light morph, 14 dark morph).  Lots of great views as they came up to the boat.  All well past Isles of Shoals.--Northern Gannet     11 all adults--Black-legged Kittiwake     42 all adults--Herring Gull     10 at Wilkinson's basin.  More in in-shore waters. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS132102278	4620	species	Atlantic Puffin	Fratercula arctica			1			United States	US	New Jersey	US-NJ	Cape May	US-NJ-009		Avalon Seawatch	L274686	H	39.1100436	-74.7088407	1995-11-27	10:30:00	w/Dave Ward	Seen flying south at a considerable distance offshore at about 10:30 AM.  The bird was first spotted by Dave Ward about half way between the "C Buoy" and the Bell Buoy or, about one mile away.  As it flew south, the distance away from us diminished to perhaps one half mile.  All observations were through a Zeiss 20 x 60 image stabilized binocular mounted on a tripod.  The viewing conditions were good with overcast skies and little if any heat shimmer over the water.  It was in sight for about one minute or perhaps slightly longer.---- The bird was small and mostly dark with a white belly.  It flew south, low over the water, occasionally obscured by swells.  Its flight was rapid and direct.  I initially thought the bird was probably a small, dark diving duck such as a female Bufflehead and I began to scan for other birds, planning to look back at it again after it got closer.  Dave insisted that I take a harder look at it, and, as it grew closer, I began to realize that it was too chunky for a Bufflehead and it seemed to lack that species' thin neck.  It also seemed that the wings were too small in proportion to the body for a duck, making me think that it was probably an alcid, though I was not yet convinced.  As it grew closer still, I realized that the wings were all dark (above and below, it seemed) as was the head.  The underparts were otherwise extensively white with a somewhat smudgy border between dark and light on the flanks.  The bird was quite chunky, reminding me of a Dovekie, though it looked a little too large and the wingbeat  was somewhat slower, not as whirring.  The dark head and somewhat smudgy flanks also seemed wrong for Dovekie and Dave and I both began to think puffin.  The most convincing views came when the bird broke the horizon for six or eight seconds, seemingly to join a Red-throated Loon which was catching up to and passing it at the same distance away.  At this point the bird was at its closest, out in the direction of the 8th Street jetty.  In this view, the body shape was clearly visible.  The head and body were one continuous shape with no constriction at the neck.  The head and body were about evenly thick all the way back to the vent area.  There was a distinct bump at the vent where the line of the underparts broke sharply upward to the very short tail.  The back was more or less flat.  The large feet were visible for the first time  in this view, protruding from the vent area and extending out even with the tail tip.  Color was not visible on the feet.  From this view it was clear that the bird was an alcid and, from shape alone, it had to be either a Dovekie or a puffin.  Fortunately, the Red-throated Loon gave a good size comparison as it flew by, and Dave and I agreed that  the alcid was almost exactly half the length of the loon.---- After the bird left, we checked field guide measurements and confirmed our suspicion that the size was exactly right for Atlantic Puffin.  The shape and plumage pattern clearly indicated a puffin as well.  Murres and Razorbill were ruled out by smaller size, chunkier shape, and entirely dark wings.  Dovekie was ruled out by larger size, slower wingbeat, dark head, and slightly smudgy flanks.  Other alcids are rather straightforward to eliminate.	obs88405	Michael	O'Brien	S9271607	eBird - Casual Observation	EBIRD				2	0		1	1
